          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Rev I. Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Charleston</placeName>
                                        <date>March 1 1850</date>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Dr Friend,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">Your esteemed<lb/> fvr of the <date>19<hi
                                                  rend="sup">th</hi></date> Ins came safe to
                                        hand<lb/> with a note to my sister, who begs me to<lb/> say
                                        in reply, that she recollects during <persName>Mr<lb/> W.
                                                  Life</persName>, of his having received the
                                        Daily<lb/> Prayer as well as the other prayers, that<lb/> he
                                        paid for the D Pryer &amp; when the others<lb/> were
                                        presented he declined taking them<lb/> because he did
                                        subscribe but for the single<lb/> volume, my sister having a
                                        complete<lb/> as well as himself.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I am as anxious as possible that<lb/> your
                                        subscribers should pay them ar<lb/>-rears regularly every
                                        year, for when<lb/> they get two or 3 years in arrears
                                        it<lb/> is difficult to collect, I will do all<lb/> I can to
                                        urge them, those in the<lb/> country I have to write to, as
                                        they<lb/> seldom are in town. <persName>Dr.
                                                  Raphael</persName><lb/> has been <add>?</add>
                                        since his<lb/> arrival, he took a Room at the Pavillion<lb/>
                                        I enclose the Proceeding of your congre</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>gation in relation to him, &amp; have<lb/> addressed you as a
                                        correspondent<lb/> not desirous of appearing in <hi
                                                  rend="underline">Person</hi><lb/> so I have given
                                        you the outline make<lb/> any <hi rend="underline">additions
                                                  &amp; corrections</hi> or <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >prefaces</hi><lb/> you think necessary, as too
                                        much<lb/> cannot be said of him, he is an<lb/> able
                                                  <add>?</add> for you &amp; I hope you<lb/> will
                                        act together, for as I told him<lb/> you were the only
                                        Israelite in<lb/>
                                        <placeName>America</placeName>, who had done work<lb/> for
                                        the cause of <placeName>Israel</placeName>, time<lb/> &amp;
                                        money have been of no consi<lb/>=deration to you for the
                                        cause &amp; ele<lb/>vation of true Judaism, He<lb/> is a
                                        great man, eloquent &amp; pro<lb/>found &amp; Logical—He has
                                        been<lb/> very unfortunate like yourself in<lb/> differing
                                        from the great <persName>Poz<lb/>=nanski</persName>—on the
                                        same day that our<lb/>
                                        <add>?</add> called &amp; as I had just finished<lb/> my
                                        address, <persName>Mr. P</persName> &amp; the commiller
                                                  <add>?</add><lb/>
                                        <persName>Hojel<add>?</add></persName> popped in &amp;
                                                  <persName>Mr P</persName> as <add>?</add>
                                        addressed<lb/> him &amp; in conclusion hoped his views<lb/>
                                        &amp; reforms coincided with the Doctor</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>&amp; the Doctor replied to him in not<lb/> the most affectionate
                                        manner, for he<lb/> could not sanction or argue with
                                        any<lb/> man or any change that would prove<lb/>
                                                  Sch<add>?</add> in <placeName>Israel</placeName>,
                                        however unimpor<lb/>tant the change, &amp; then <persName>Mr
                                                  P.</persName> undertook<lb/> in the presence of
                                        all the visitors &amp; step<lb/>-ping from the object of his
                                        visit,<lb/> went more fully in to the <del>reforms</del>
                                        innovations of his<lb/> congregation &amp; himself—the
                                        conversation<lb/> lasted about 2 Hours as <persName>Mr
                                                  P.</persName> had to<lb/> leave on business but
                                        desired to continue<lb/> the Discussion, when <persName>Mr
                                                  Rosenfeldt</persName> sug<lb/>=gested that the
                                        discussion or friendly con<lb/>versation be <add>?</add>
                                        before Both<lb/> congregations at Hebrew Orphan Hall on<lb/>
                                        the <date>Sunday</date> following which was agreed<lb/> to
                                        by the Dr. I was much opposed to it the<lb/> more I
                                        reflected upon it &amp; it was not un<lb/>-til the
                                                  <date>Thursday</date> follg that I gave my
                                        consent<lb/> because I know his followers would not<lb/>
                                        admit their errors &amp; it was a <add>?</add> of<lb/> time
                                        &amp; words.—The meeting took place<lb/> &amp; I need not
                                        tell you the result, <persName>Mr<lb/> P</persName> was as a
                                        child in the hands of a giant</p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>Before the Doctor would go into an<lb/> examination of the
                                        introduction of an<lb/> organ or the discontinuance of
                                        the<lb/> use of the 2d day of Festivals, of which<lb/>
                                        <persName>Mr. P</persName> had brought a cartload of
                                        Books,<lb/> the Doctor took him &amp; his followers
                                        “all<lb/> a back” (as the suitors say) &amp; struck<lb/> at
                                        the root of innovation, &amp; the<lb/> main stay of Judaism.
                                        The Creed<lb/> —the addition &amp; the total abolition<lb/>
                                        of a portion The non <sic>fullfilment</sic><lb/> of the
                                        prophecy of the messiah—&amp; the resurrection<lb/> of the
                                        Dead, which last article<lb/> you are aware of is not
                                        upon<lb/> their tablet in the synagogue</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">To give you an account of the<lb/> conversation
                                        would occupy too<lb/> much time &amp; paper, but the
                                        con<lb/>clusion &amp; <add>?</add> of <persName>Dr
                                                  R</persName>, of <persName>nu<lb/> Pos</persName>
                                        is that he is either a fool or<lb/> knave, for he has
                                        hitherto palmed<lb/> on us, as <persName>Albo</persName>'
                                        opinion &amp; he thought<lb/> he could do it upon the Dr.
                                        the<lb/> opinions of others, which <persName>Albo</persName>
                                        refutes<lb/> most powerfully &amp; which agrees with me<lb/>
                                        great sagery &amp; the great Marmonides</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">It so happened that the Doctor in his<lb/>
                                        excitement could not refer to the part<lb/> but he had
                                        translated it &amp; is in the <add>?</add><lb/>
                                                  Rev<add>?</add> &amp; promised his audience to
                                        have<lb/> it reprinted at his own expense to<lb/> verify his
                                        assertion, he has done so</p>
                              <pb n="5"/>
                              <p>But such a mokkas as <persName>P</persName> &amp; his<lb/>
                                        followers obtained was as merited<lb/> as it was severe. He
                                        told them<lb/> they were <add>?</add> Jews. For
                                        <add>?</add><lb/> are jews but those who believe in<lb/> the
                                        written &amp; oral Laws. The coming<lb/> of the Messiah
                                        &amp; the resurrection of<lb/> the dead.—They all felt the
                                        rebuke<lb/> &amp; they all say he is of course a<lb/> Bigot
                                        like you, I suppose you'll<lb/> say you like to be in such
                                        com<lb/>-pany if <lb/><persName>Dr. R</persName> is a bigot.
                                        The most<lb/> conspicuous of those who have felt<lb/> the
                                        truth of <persName>Dr R</persName> castigation is<lb/>
                                        <persName>Dr Philip Cohen</persName>, to whom the Dr<lb/>
                                        had brought a letter from <persName>A Hart</persName><lb/>
                                        &amp; to whom <persName>Mr Josh Lazarus</persName> had
                                        sent<lb/> to me tickets for his lectures to dis<lb/>pose of
                                        &amp; to show how small a mat<lb/>ter it was he returned
                                        them in a<lb/> note saying “that the illiberal cause<lb/> of
                                                  <persName>Dr R</persName> will prevent him from
                                        dis<lb/>posing of the tickets, so you see<lb/> that the Dr
                                        might have made</p>
                              <pb n="6"/>
                              <p>20 or 40 Dolls. but it so happens<lb/> that one Lecture had already
                                        taken<lb/> place &amp; yet <persName>Mr Cohen</persName> had
                                        not<lb/> distributed or used even a single<lb/> ticket—His
                                        Lectures therefore has<lb/> been attended by a most
                                        respec<lb/>table audience, but not so nume<lb/>-rous as I
                                        could have worked through<lb/>
                                        <add>?</add> proportionate to our<lb/> population I am
                                        pleased to say that<lb/> all the Israelites in our city with
                                        one or two<lb/> exceptions have attended his lectures<lb/>
                                        &amp; have been most agreeable enter<lb/>tained &amp;
                                        enlightened, he again Lectures<lb/> tomorrow at our Shool
                                        XXXVI Ezekiel<lb/>
                                        <add>?</add> XXIV—&amp; on <date>Sunday</date> he addresses
                                        our<lb/> children &amp; teachers of the school.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I must stop <persName>Mr Levin</persName> is
                                        pre<lb/>paring an account of the<lb/> conversation &amp;
                                        intends sending it to<lb/> you. I have also sent a copy<lb/>
                                        of the proceedings as enclosed to the<lb/> Asmoneon—if not
                                        too late for the<lb/>
                                        <date>March</date> Occident will you mend<lb/> it? I
                                                  <add>?</add> you are well</p>
                              <pb n="7"/>
                              <p>in which I am yours by all<lb/>
                                        <add>?</add> I remain<add>?</add></p>
                              <p rend="indent(10)">Your friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(10)">&amp; well wisher</p>
                              <p rend="indent(10)">
                                        <persName role="author">Samuel Hart Sen</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>The Doctor will leave for <placeName>Savan<lb/>-nah</placeName> on
                                                  <date>Thursday</date> next, where<lb/> he will
                                        lecture on <date>Saturday</date> night<lb/> &amp; thence
                                        retrace his steps to <placeName>MS</placeName><lb/> not
                                        having time <add>?</add> him to<lb/> visit <placeName>New
                                                  Orleans</placeName> &amp; return to
                                                  <placeName>NC</placeName><lb/> by the
                                                  <date>Passover</date>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I should have been highly gra<lb/>tified to have
                                        had you here this<lb/> week most especially, but hope<lb/>
                                        you will soon <add>?</add> in upon us</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I forgot to say that <persName>Dr Wise</persName>
                                        arrived<lb/> here last week &amp; delivered his 1<hi
                                                  rend="sup">st</hi> Lec<lb/>-ture on
                                                  <date>Saturday</date> afternoon, but it did
                                        me<lb/> great pleasure <add>?</add> when members<lb/> had
                                        heard the great <persName>Raphael</persName> in the<lb/>
                                        morning, on <date>Sunday</date> he helped his
                                                  <sic>Proty<lb/>-type</sic>, &amp; on
                                                  <date>Monday</date> eve (<date>Purim</date>) he
                                        told his<lb/> congregation that they would not &amp; could
                                        not<lb/> as American Jews think of going back</p>
                              <pb n="8"/>
                              <p>to <placeName>Jerusalem</placeName> to be under the<lb/> messiah a
                                                  <hi rend="underline">King</hi> when</p>
                    </body>
